metadata.name: Fields of the Abandoned Homeland #82
metadata.description:
This project was started in December 2021. At that time, I didn't know what the result would be. It was only an idea to create something memorable, you know, like a photo that people keep in their wallets, or a picture on someone's office desk, something that evokes warm and nostalgic emotions. I didn't have a specific plan, so I just focused on testing different mechanics that might be useful in my future drop. And then, in February 2022, the war came to my home. For two weeks, my family and I hid from bombs and rockets in the basement of our house, and finally, we were lucky enough to escape. We have been looking for a safe place to stay for months, and with several relocations, depression set in, and it was difficult to believe what was happening. I thought that such events only happened in movies and history textbooks. The only way to distract myself was by coding. And then, during one of our relocations, I realized what should be the main idea of this project. This is what I had watched for hours during every relocation. Whether it was a bus ride or a train ride, only the background changed, but the landscape was almost the same - endless Ukrainian wheat fields. Fields, some of which were occupied, burned, or simply turned into minefields. Fields symbolized by the yellow color on the flag of Ukraine. These are the fields I want to see again but in reverse order, on my way home. 

I dedicate this drop to everyone who, for whatever reason, had to leave their home against their will.

In live mode:
- Press [1]-[4] to change resolution
- Press [s] to save

Made with p5js and hope
Copyright @Kitel87 || 2023

metadata.name: glory hole$ #584
metadata.description:
our consciousness as humans can be distilled into a crudely fashioned hole at an abandoned dave & busters and the meditative state that is endured while sitting on a neglected toilet praying for the sound of disrupted waters. glory holes embody anonymity and pleasure for pleasure's sake. they are creations that cannot be destroyed, as they exist in the memories of anyone who uses or witnesses. many speculate that the carving of the hole is the purest form of human ingenuity and the desire to explore the unknown. formerly limited to the physical space. these glory holes transcend space and time. and exist in that same unknown that tempts us all. legalize ground beef. create nothing. consume everything.

HUGE thank you to @PureSpider for the layered PNG template, this dream would not have been realized without you friend.

metadata.name: Hegemony of Screensavers (Artifacts) #55
metadata.description: A randomized composition of digital artifacts. Scans of plaster, 3D printed objects and natural stone. iPhone 5s. Inefficient GLSL. Screensaver trails. Nonlinear dynamics with Den Tsucs and Wang-Sun attractors. Distilled hours, days and weeks.

metadata.name: Avaritia #41
metadata.description:
A third and final study of the human figure through code. Can a generative artwork be unsettling?  

If some don't resemble people, I apologize, and would be keen to refund or trade with you. This is partly the reason for releasing the work at low price. After spending a futile time trying to remove 'bad' outputs, I came to realize that's absolutely achievable, but at the expense of removing the surprise outputs.... The ones that kept me returning to this work over the course of 7 months. 

There's a second side to the low price.... I'd like this to be a small statement against greed within the generative art space over the last few years. Greed of artists – greed of marketplaces – greed of collectors – greed of flippers. We were all too greedy. But there's a positive ending to my rant, because for us remainders, we're still here, down deep in digital art. 

Much love, and a small measuring of greed, 
Tenebris.Via 
2024


Additional params 
- &fullsize=true : Force output to occupy full screen width 
- &png=true : Download 2100x2970 png file 
- &svg=true : Download svg file 
- &theme={number} : Use "4" for plotter theme, with fixed-width black lines 
- &interval={number} : The higher the number, the less layers generated. Usually 4-16 
- &minlen={number} : Remove linepaths below {number} minimum length. Usually 50-500 
- &maxlen={number} : Remove linepaths above {number} maximum length. Usually 2000+ 

e.g. ?theme=4&interval=12&minlen=500

While the work is plottable, there can be a fair bit of trial and error to produce good results. Play around with the interval, minlen and maxlen params to suit. Inkscape is a great tool to help. 

Opensource libs 
- simplex noise implementation in JS : https://github.com/jwagner/simplex-noise.js 
- deterministic JS random methods : https://github.com/strainer/fdrandom.js 
- static indexer for 2D points : https://github.com/mourner/kdbush

metadata.name: Contort #142
metadata.description:
Contort is the result of combining several previously meaningless experiments and learnings into a single cohesive algorithm. The project comes in a variety of shapes, bends, twists, colors, and other variations.  

The artwork builds towards the end-result by rendering a fixed number of forms per frame to ensure a smooth rendering process. Rendering times can vary depending on which features are combined by the hash.

metadata.name: Lands of Solitude #83
metadata.description:
In times of chaos and uncertainty while the digital world falls appart, some will decide to resist and build. In their blind quest for curiosity, knowledge and creation, they will endure the darkest times and as waves of departures will follow one another, very few will remain. These are the lands of solitude that await.

Controls :
* Drag and pan to rotate and zoom.
* Press « F » to toggle the All-Over mode.
* Press « G » to toggle the grid.
* Press « H » to toggle the in-world infos.
* Press the space bar to toggle the auto scroll mode.
* Press « R » to restart.

———————

Lands of Solitude by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
Made with Unity

metadata.name: Giants of the Meadow #7
metadata.description:
For my first drop on the new fxhash v1.0 I wanted to make something different. So I challenged myself to write a raymarcher like the ones I use in my shaders but in p5.js and make a fully procedural scene with it. It's a bit tricky to work with vectors once you are used to GLSL, but I managed to write a decent algorithm that scans a grid and slowly draws the image. It draws it with circles and triangles for the grass. The first thing I used for testing was a SDF of a plane with some tall bars on it. Then I was trying different distortions on the shapes and in one moment the results gave me the idea of a scene with mushrooms and grass on an undulated terrain. Later I added a small river and a cloudy sky. I think I was inadvertently inspired by some children's books I had when I was a kid. 

Best viewed full screen.

Features:

Mood: happy - normal - melancholic - strange - sleepy
Mushrooms: 2 - 4 (sometimes one of the mushrooms can only be seen on full screen)
Mushroom height: short - medium - tall
Mushroom fatness: S - M - L - XL
Mushroom shape: 1 - 2 - 3- 4 - 5
Mushroom tilt
Flowers color: white - yellow - pink - cyan - multicolor
River: yes - no
Camera orientation: north - south

metadata.name: NFT #66
metadata.description:
This is NFT - Non-Fungible Token released at fxhash.xyz by Shvembldr.

This art is not resolution agnostic and may vary on different devices and screens.

It doesn't make any sense, it's just geometric shapes and moving dots. Sometimes it looks like a liquid splashing to the surface, sometimes it looks like nothing. But it's nice to watch (most of the time).

Buy it only if you like it!

Click = pause
S = save png
(Live Mode)

metadata.name: Penumbra #74
metadata.description:
Penumbra is a geometric exploration of the possible outcomes from 3 basic rules:

1) Place some walls
2) Place some light sources
3) Draw the resulting shadows

This series is a small thank you to the collectors of Umbra :)

metadata.name: Little Trees #105
metadata.description:
Delicate, little trees. Some with green leaves, some with orange, some with red. This is the genesis project of Brian Gawlik.

The default resolution is 3600x3600. To redraw and save as an image at a different resolution - in the live view, open your browser's devtools and execute the function saveImg(pixWidth) where pixWidth is the desired width in pixels of the image. For example, saveImg(4096) will prompt you to download a 4096x4096 image. It is recommended not to export below 2400x2400 as this will compromise the aesthetic of the shadow.

metadata.name: Dialog Box #223
metadata.description:
Dialog Box is a playful generative art project that invites viewers to engage with the concept of choice in the digital age. Inspired by the early Mac OS, the artwork presents an interface of two buttons, each symbolizing a choice steeped in 80s and 90s pop culture, from the serious to the lighthearted.

https://medium.com/@duaneking/dialog-box-by-duane-king-scott-brewer-and-adam-moliski-abab7afd3519

metadata.name: Escape Plans #89
metadata.description:
This work is part of a series of Generative Tokens that combine a catalogue of images created inside The Sims 4 with more recent explorations towards pixel art and game history in the aim of exhausting and discovering new narratives inside the world created for my game art collection Contain Real Ingredients, minted in Teia through the last year. In this case, the subject is the ever present in gaming: escape.

Image composition made using PureSpider template.
Reload if anything seems off.

metadata.name: little god #274
metadata.description:
All of our strong emotions, feelings and experiences come from childhood. Sincere happiness or frightening cruelty is primarily inherent in children, so they learn about the world. When we were children, we first hurt someone, first burst into tears from resentment, learned what is good and what is bad. 
Our parents did not answer our questions, either because they did not know the answer or because they thought we were too young. We learned to look for the answers ourselves. Whoever says that children don't understand is a fool. They do understand, but they do it in their own way. The world as seen through the eyes of a child is not like the world as seen through the eyes of an adult. It is often not built on the laws of physics or the laws of the marketplace. In a child's world or universe, the moon is just a little light in the sky, and the next street is already a different country. Their world is built on speculation and magical theories. Unfortunately, a child's world is not eternal. As they grow up, the "real" life, the life of adults, pokes into them like a sharp needle over and over again. 
There is something incredibly tragic about this time gap between child and adult. It is this period that I wanted to trace in my work. As teenagers, it is as if we are between two trains, we are no longer children, but we are not yet adults. We get to know ourselves, we test our strength and readiness to exist in the "real" world. We are trying to find our place in the unfriendly world of adults, but we are also not ready to let go of the magic of childhood. It confuses, torments, and frustrates us. But it is a necessary and unavoidable tragedy. 

Code by PureSpider
